      <H1><FONT face=3D"Times New Roman" size=3D+4><I>BFF=20
Usage</I></FONT></H1></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D628 bgColor=3D#006666 height=3D21><B><FONT=20
      face=3DArial,Helvetica>INSTALLING BFF</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D628 height=3D104>
      <UL>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Copy the ZIP distribution file =
to any=20
        directory that is NOT listed in the 3ds max Plugins paths or =
Startup=20
        scripts settings.</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Unzip the distribution file =
</FONT>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Launch 3ds max - version 4, 5 =
or 6</FONT>=20

        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Go to Main =
Menu&gt;MAXScript&gt;Run=20
        Script...</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Find and select the BFF .ms =
file </FONT>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Go to Main =
Menu&gt;Customize&gt;Customize=20
        User Interface...</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>In the Toolbars tab, locate the =
Category=20
        "Bobo_s Tools"</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Drag the entry "BFF_Exporter" =
to a=20
        toolbar.</FONT> </LI></UL></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D628 bgColor=3D#006666 height=3D21><B><FONT=20
      face=3DArial,Helvetica>EXPORTING A SCENE USING =
BFF</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D628 height=3D104>
      <UL>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Press the button on the toolbar =
to open=20
        the Exporter dialog.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>The dialog provides options to =
export or=20
        skip specific object classes. Check the ones you want to export. =

        Usually, you will just leave these settings to their=20
        defaults.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>The Preferences group lets you =
control=20
        some additional features: </FONT>
        <UL>
          <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Check "Collapse Stack" to =
force stack=20
          collapsing. Generally, BFF will collapse most objects to =
Editable Mesh=20
          as it does not support most modifiers. Some objects can =
preserve their=20
          modifier stack though, for example a Box or Sphere primitive =
or a Text=20
          shape with an Extrude modifier on top will be exported =
correclty=20
          preserving the stack. Checking this option will force BFF to =
export=20
          even these objects as meshes.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>=20
          <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Uncheck the "Animation" =
button to=20
          disallow the export of Postion/Rotation and Scale animation=20
          controllers.<BR>&nbsp; </FONT>
          <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Uncheck the "Material Editor" =
button to=20
          disable the export of the 24 Material Editor =
materials.<BR>&nbsp;=20
          </FONT>
          <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Check the "ZIP Archive" =
button to=20
          create a ZIP file containing all exported files. The files =
will NOT be=20
          deleted from the disk, so you will end up with a ZIPped and =
regular=20
          version of the export. You can use the ZIP file to copy to =
another=20
          machine and import there.<BR>&nbsp; </FONT>
          <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Uncheck the "Progress Report" =
button to=20
          disable the progress dialog which appears when importing. This =
might=20
          be useful when exporting to MAX 2.5 which does not support the =

          features of the progress dialog.<BR>&nbsp; </FONT>
          <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>Check the "Selected Only" =
button to=20
          export only the selected portions of the scene.<BR>&nbsp;=20
        </FONT></LI></UL>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>To export the current scene, =
press the=20
        "EXPORT SCENE" resp. "EXPORT SELECTED OBJECTS" button. A file =
selection=20
        dialog will open. Enter the name of the export file to write to =
and=20
        press the "Save" button. You can export to any directory you =
want. Note=20
        that a number of sub-directories will be created at the target =
path to=20
        accomodate all exported data.</FONT>
        <P> </P></LI></UL></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D628 bgColor=3D#006666 height=3D21><B><FONT=20
      face=3DArial,Helvetica>IMPORTING A BFF SCENE </FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD width=3D628 height=3D104>
      <UL>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>You don't need an importer - =
the BFF=20
        export generates a set of MAXScript files and BFF data files =
which=20
        already include the necessary importer code. This also means =
that while=20
        the results from different BFF exporter versions might look and =
work=20
        differently, they will always import correctly and are =
independent of=20
        future changes to the file format.<BR>&nbsp;</FONT>=20
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>You can import the scene in any =
3ds max=20
        version - 3.x, 4.x, 5.x or 6. (2.5 is only partially supported =
when no=20
        Progress Dialog info is included). Only the objects and data =
supported=20
        by the target platform will be imported, the rest will be =
skipped. For=20
        example, you cannot import texture coordinates to 2.5 at all and =
only=20
        using a DLX extension to 3.x<BR>&nbsp; </FONT>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>To import a scene, go to Main=20
        Menu&gt;MAXScript&gt;Run Script.... and select the base .MS file =

        exported by BFF. This will set the current directory to the path =
the=20
        base file is located in and will ensure the import can proceed =
through=20
        all other files. Trying to evaluate a base .MS file without =
using the=20
        Run Script... dialog might lead to incomplete imports.<BR>&nbsp; =
</FONT>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>A Reset Scene prompt will =
appear - if you=20
        want to merge the scene with your current scene, press No. If =
you want=20
        to replace the scene, select Yes.<BR>&nbsp; </FONT>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica>A progress dialog will open (as =
long as=20
        it has been included on export) showing you information about =
the=20
        importing process. Tasks will be marked with &gt;, success =
messages with=20
        +. failure messages with --, warnings with !!<BR>&nbsp; </FONT>
        <LI><FONT face=3DArial,Helvetica><B>NOTE</B>: In order to import =
texture=20
        coordinates to 3D Studio MAX R3.x, you will need to install an=20
        additional MAXScript Extension - <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.scriptspot.com/Extensions/Wads/Wad-O-Extensions!-v3_2/=
MAXr3Scripts-Extensions-SimonFeltman-MultiMap.zip">MultiMap=20
        DLX by Simon Feltman</A>. BFF will try both the 3ds max 4 =
mapping=20
        methods and the R3 MultiMap methods and use the one that works =
without=20
        additionally checking the current software version. If the DLX =
is not=20
        installed under R3, no texture mapping coordinates will be=20
        imported!</FONT> </LI></UL></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR>
